/* ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
   CONDITION GLOSSARY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════ */
const GLOSSARY = [
  {
    term:"Centering",
    category:"Structure",
    short:"The balance of white border on each side of the card.",
    full:"Centering measures how evenly the card's artwork sits within its printed borders, expressed as a ratio — 50/50 is perfect. PSA measures left-to-right and top-to-bottom separately. A card can be perfectly centred on the horizontal axis but badly off on the vertical. PSA 10 requires 60/40 or better on both axes. PSA 9 allows 65/35. Beyond 70/30 and you're looking at PSA 8 or lower. Centering is the single most common reason a card misses PSA 10 — it's a factory issue, not a handling issue, and nothing can fix it after the fact.",
  },
  {
    term:"Whitening",
    category:"Corners & Edges",
    short:"White stress marks at card corners or edges, caused by handling or wear.",
    full:"Whitening appears when the printed surface layer of a card is compressed or abraded, exposing the white card stock beneath. It shows most visibly on dark-bordered cards (Base Set, many vintage sets) and at corner tips where handling pressure concentrates. A single white dot on a corner tip is enough to drop a card from PSA 10 to PSA 9. Heavy whitening across all four corners signals PSA 7 or below. On cards with white borders, whitening is less visually obvious but graders still check under loupe magnification.",
  },
  {
    term:"Fraying",
    category:"Corners & Edges",
    short:"Fibrous splitting or peeling at card corners.",
    full:"Fraying occurs when the layers of the card stock begin to separate at a corner, creating a frayed, fibrous appearance — similar to a worn book corner. It is distinct from whitening: whitening is a surface discolouration, fraying is a structural separation. Any visible fraying under normal light is a PSA 8 at best. Significant fraying across multiple corners pushes a card into PSA 6 or lower territory. Fraying cannot be repaired — attempting to press or glue corners back together constitutes card alteration and will result in a PSA Authentic (Altered) grade.",
  },
  {
    term:"Edge wear",
    category:"Corners & Edges",
    short:"Nicks, chips, or roughness along any of the four card edges.",
    full:"The four edges of a card — top, bottom, left, right — are vulnerable to nicks and chips from sliding in and out of binders, loose storage in boxes, or contact with other cards. PSA graders run a finger along each edge and examine under light. A single noticeable nick on one edge is typically a PSA 8. Multiple chips or rough edges across several sides drops a card toward PSA 6–7. Edge wear is often caused by improper storage — cards kept loose in a box or stacked without sleeves almost always show edge damage.",
  },
  {
    term:"Surface scratches",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"Fine lines on the card surface from contact with other objects.",
    full:"Surface scratches are lines in the printed surface or protective laminate caused by contact with other cards, binder pages, or hard surfaces. They range from micro-scratches only visible under raking light to deep scratches that catch the eye immediately. PSA 10 requires a surface that is essentially scratch-free under normal examination. A single fine scratch visible under direct light is typically enough to prevent PSA 10. Deep or multiple scratches push a card toward PSA 8 or lower. Surface scratches are the hardest flaw to detect in photos — the raking light technique (lamp held low and to one side) is the most reliable way to reveal them.",
  },
  {
    term:"Print lines",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"Fine lines in the card's print layer from the manufacturing process.",
    full:"Print lines are manufacturing defects — thin lines running across part or all of the card surface, caused by imperfections in the printing rollers or plates during production. They are not caused by handling and cannot be avoided by the collector. Print lines are assessed differently by different graders: PSA may still award a high grade if lines are very fine, while BGS sub-grades surface condition strictly. Print lines are often invisible under flat light but very visible under raking light or magnification. They are most common on certain print runs — Base Set Unlimited and some Japanese sets are known for high print line frequency.",
  },
  {
    term:"Print defects",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"Ink spots, colour registration errors, or missing ink from manufacturing.",
    full:"Print defects include ink spots (small blobs of ink outside the intended artwork), colour misregistration (where one colour layer is slightly offset from others, creating a blurry or doubled look), and ink voids (areas where ink failed to apply, leaving a pale or blank patch). These are factory defects present from the moment the card was printed. Minor print defects may still allow a PSA 9. Significant defects — visible ink blobs, obvious misregistration in the artwork — cap a card at PSA 8 or below. Some print defect cards have collector value as error cards, but standard grading penalises them.",
  },
  {
    term:"Halo effect",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"A glowing or blurred light halo around card artwork, from ink bleeding.",
    full:"The halo effect (also called ink bleed or colour bleed) appears as a subtle glow or blur around the artwork border, where ink from one print layer has spread slightly into an adjacent area. It is most visible on cards with high-contrast borders — dark artwork against a light background. A mild halo is generally tolerated by PSA and may still grade PSA 9 or even PSA 10 for less strict graders. A pronounced halo that noticeably blurs the artwork border is a defect that typically caps a card at PSA 8.",
  },
  {
    term:"Factory crease",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"A crease present in the card from manufacturing, before it ever left the pack.",
    full:"Factory creases are creases that exist in a card before it was ever placed in a pack — caused by the automatic collation and packaging machinery. They are not caused by handling or poor storage. PSA can authenticate factory creases as such and will note them on the label. A factory creased card receives a Qualifier grade — for example, PSA 8 (OC) for off-centre, or a note indicating the crease. Factory creases do not significantly increase or decrease the card's collectability for most buyers, but they do prevent a clean numeric grade.",
  },
  {
    term:"Indent",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"A physical dent or depression in the card surface without breaking the surface layer.",
    full:"An indent is a physical depression in the card stock — the card has been pressed or impacted hard enough to deform the cardboard, but without cracking or breaking the surface layer. Indents are usually caused by sharp objects pressing against a card in storage, or by damage during shipping. They show clearly under raking light as a shadow or recessed area. Any noticeable indent is at minimum a PSA 8 issue. Deep or multiple indents push into PSA 6–7 territory. Unlike surface scratches, indents cannot be present without affecting the card's structure.",
  },
  {
    term:"Staining",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"Discolouration from liquid contact, oxidation, or environmental exposure.",
    full:"Staining covers any discolouration of the card surface or borders from an external source: liquid contact (water, oil, drinks), environmental oxidation (yellowing of white borders on very old cards), or adhesive residue (from price stickers or tape). White border yellowing on vintage cards is extremely common — Base Set cards from 1999 often show border yellowing from 25 years of environmental exposure. Significant staining is a PSA 6 or lower issue. Light staining or minor yellowing may still grade PSA 8 depending on location and visibility.",
  },
  {
    term:"Gloss",
    category:"Surface",
    short:"The reflective sheen on a card's surface — its presence or absence indicates condition.",
    full:"Pokémon cards are printed with a protective gloss laminate over the surface. In pristine condition, this gloss is even and fully intact. Surface wear, scratches, and handling gradually dull and degrade the gloss — a card with flat, dull patches where gloss has worn away signals surface damage even when no individual scratches are visible. PSA graders assess gloss consistency as part of surface evaluation. A card with fully intact, even gloss across the entire surface is a strong PSA 10 candidate on the surface criterion. Uneven or patchy gloss is typically a PSA 8–9 surface.",
  },
  {
    term:"PSA Population (Pop Report)",
    category:"Grading Terms",
    short:"The total number of cards graded at each PSA grade level, published publicly.",
    full:"PSA maintains a public database — the Population Report or Pop Report — showing how many copies of every card have been graded and at what grade level. A card with a PSA 10 population of 5 is extremely scarce in top grade; a card with a PSA 10 population of 5,000 is common. Population directly affects value: low-pop PSA 10s command significant premiums over high-pop cards of the same nominal grade. Collectors check the Pop Report before submitting to understand how rare a top-grade copy is likely to be. Access the PSA Pop Report at psacard.com/pop.",
  },
  {
    term:"Gem Mint",
    category:"Grading Terms",
    short:"PSA's highest grade — PSA 10. Near-perfect condition.",
    full:"Gem Mint is PSA's top grade, awarded as PSA 10. A Gem Mint card must have four perfectly sharp corners with no fraying or whitening visible to the naked eye, edges with no nicks or chips, a surface free of scratches and print defects under normal examination, and centering of 60/40 or better on both axes. The card must appear as if it came directly from the pack. Gem Mint is the grade all serious collectors chase — it commands the largest value premiums and the lowest populations for vintage cards.",
  },
  {
    term:"Qualifier",
    category:"Grading Terms",
    short:"A PSA designation indicating an otherwise high-grade card has one specific flaw.",
    full:"A Qualifier grade is assigned when a card would receive a high numeric grade (typically 8–10) except for one specific, identifiable issue. Common qualifiers: (OC) for off-centre — the card is pristine except for centering outside normal parameters; (MK) for marked — an otherwise excellent card with a specific mark or stamp; (ST) for stain. A PSA 9 (OC) card is still in near-mint condition except for its centering. Qualifier grades generally trade at a discount to clean grades but can still be valuable for rare cards where any high-grade example is scarce.",
  },
  {
    term:"Raw",
    category:"Grading Terms",
    short:"An ungraded card, not submitted to PSA or any other grading company.",
    full:"A raw card is simply an ungraded card — one that has not been submitted to PSA, BGS, CGC, or any other grading service. Raw cards are stored in sleeves, top-loaders, or binders and priced based on their apparent condition. Raw pricing is inherently uncertain because condition is self-assessed. The entire point of professional grading is to replace raw subjective assessment with a standardised, authenticated grade. TCGscout is a raw card assessment tool — it helps you evaluate a raw card before deciding whether to submit it for professional grading.",
  },
];

